<div id="review_976156890" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/976156890" />
    <a title="Kevin Cole" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30676945-kevin-cole"><img alt="Kevin Cole" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464710448p2/30676945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/976156890?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin Cole" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin Cole" href="/user/show/30676945-kevin-cole">Kevin Cole</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer976156890" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15669790530639087868">S.J. Perelman is like a disease: He will attack without hesitation and with a single-mindedness that can throw you for a loop. One of his little stories or whatever they are have more going on, stylistically, than many novels. You don&apos;t have to get all the pop culture references that were common in his day and a mystery to us in order to get the gist of his jokes. That being said, if you like a little drama to go with your polemic, Perelman&apos;s not your guy. He&apos;s best in small doses, spaced-out. P</span>
  <span id="freeText15669790530639087868" style="display:none">S.J. Perelman is like a disease: He will attack without hesitation and with a single-mindedness that can throw you for a loop. One of his little stories or whatever they are have more going on, stylistically, than many novels. You don't have to get all the pop culture references that were common in his day and a mystery to us in order to get the gist of his jokes. That being said, if you like a little drama to go with your polemic, Perelman's not your guy. He's best in small doses, spaced-out. Pure wit. That's it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15669790530639087868" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
